I think I spoke to soon on that, these are actually highly composable. I've gone through all the hooks libs, and I don't see anything that would be hard. They actually have some benefits over hooks:
* Use order doesn't matter, you can conditionally use() whatever you want, everything is declared in init(), so this issue goes away
* Props supports both atomic composition or de-composition of a complex item like a Widget because it can wrap the view in additional Widgets. 

Also since they are classes, they support all the classic styles of code re-use. Inheritence, implementation, composition. 

For example, this is the entire `TapProp`, it just extends `GestureDetectorProp` which is itself just a wrapper around `GestureDetector`
```
class TapProp extends GestureDetectorProp {
  TapProp(VoidCallback onTap) : super(onTap: onTap);
}
```

You can do basic memo like this:
```
ValueProp<MyThing> thing;
onInit(){
   thing = addProp((_, w) => ValueProp(MyThing()));
}
onPressed() => thing.value = getNewThing(); //View rebuilds
```

In this case the ValueProp is encapsulating the common low level logic of optimizing builds if nothing has changed. This is the entire `Prop`:
```
class ValueProp<T> extends StatefulProp<ValueProp<T>> {
  ValueProp(this._value);
  T _value;
  T get value => _value;
  set value(T value) {
    if (value == _value) return;
    setState(() =>_value = value;);
  }}
```

Then all my primitive types can just extend that one Prop:
```
class IntProp extends ValueProp<int> {
  IntProp([int defaultValue = 0]) : super(defaultValue);
}

class BoolProp extends ValueProp<bool> {
  BoolProp([bool defaultValue = false]) : super(defaultValue);

  void toggle() => value = !value;
}

class DoubleProp extends ValueProp<double> {
  DoubleProp([double defaultValue = 0]) : super(defaultValue);
}

```

The last step would be to inject the `.addProp` and `.syncProp` methods to the Props. Then they could truly compose eachother:
```
class PropA extends StatefulProp<PropA> {
  
  @override
  void init() {
    _propB = addProp(PropB());
  }
}
```

The Tap handler above could then be written with composition over inheritance, as:
```
class TapProp extends StatefulProp<TapProp> {
  TapProp(this.onTap);
  final VoidCallback onTap;
  @override
  void init() {
    addProp(GestureDetectorProp(onTap: onTap));
  }
}
```

Because the a Prop is just a simple class with a few callbacks, there's really no limit to what you can do, or how you can compose them together. It just gets the benefit of also having a `override Widget build(Widget child){  // Wrap Widgets Here! }` so the Props can tie into the RenderTree as well.

