Important to remember, you just need to take 5 mores lines, and you can move to Stateful, and all the `use()` and `Prop<>` stuff goes away. This is just to enable simple use cases in Stateless style, but the Stateful is still there if you want the more straightforward setup/usage.

But ya, we can only go so far with `dart`, I hit a lot of walls with dart trying to implement this. Weak enum support, no reflection, etc really add up to a lot of dead ends architecturally. 

It certainly would be nice to have some `state` keyword ot something, that went from this:
```
class MyView extends PropsWidget<MyView>{
  MyView(this.duration);
  final Duration duration;

  static PropRef<BoolProp> _bool1 = PropRef();
  static PropRef<AnimatorControllerProp> _anim1 = PropRef();

  @override
  void initProps(){
    addProp(_bool1, false);
    syncProp(_anim1, (c, w) => AnimatorControllerProp(duration: w.duration, vsync: c.read<TickerProvider>()));
  }

 @override
  void buildWithProps(){
      // Setting `useRef(_bool1).value = true` would rebuild the view  automatically 
    return FadeTransition(opacity: useProp(_anim1).controller, child: Text("${useProp(_bool1).value}"));
  }
}
```

To This: 
```
class MyView extends PropsWidget<MyView>{
  MyView(this.duration);
  final Duration duration;

 state BoolProp _bool1 = addProp( false);
 state AnimatorControllerProp _anim1 = syncProp(
     (c, w) => AnimatorControllerProp(duration: w.duration, vsync: c.read<TickerProvider>()));

 @override
  void buildWithProps(){
    return FadeTransition(opacity: anim1.controller, child: Text("${_bool1.value}"));
  }
}
```
If that `state` keyword were introduced, I believe `StatelessWidget` would be fully deprecated. As is it still has a place because of the slightly cludgy stateless usage.

But now we're into verbosity, which we all agreed off the top was not the _primary_ need here. This certainly addresses the core issue of code-reuse across widgets.

If dart's enum support wasn't so limited, we could have some interesting convention like: 
```
class MyView extends PropsWidget {
  enum p { isLoading , fadeAnim,  scrollAnim}
  
  initProps(){
    addProp(p.isLoading, BoolProp(false));
    addProp(p.fadeAnim, AnimationControllerProp(Duration(seconds: 1)));
    syncProp(p.scrollAnim, (c, w) => AnimationControllerProp(Duration(seconds: w.duration)))
  }
  
  buildWithProps(){
     print(use(p.isLoading).value);
  }
  void restartFade() => use(p.fadeAnim).controller.forward(from: 0);
  set isLoading(value) => use(p.isLoading).value = value; //View would rebuild
}
```
This doesn't rely on using static keys, and comes in at very low line-count.

Downside is I don't see how you make it compile safe. need each item to have it's own T
