Working on a `TimerProp` shows a nice use case.

If I want to delay something, but the user navigates away before the delay has expired:
```
// This will blow up, unless I put some hacky check inside the closure, or null out the controller and add?null?checks.
Future.delayed(Duration(seconds: 1), () => controller.forward());

// This will blow up, unless I keep a handle around, and remember to override dispose() (+4-6 lines and/or potential bug)
Timer(Duration(seconds: 1), () => controller.forward());

// This is completely safe, cause the prop just kills it's timer when widget is unmounted. 
addProp(TimerProp(1, (_) => controller.forward()));
```

The entire TimerProp is 20 lines, and no Widget ever again has to worry about this issue:
```
class TimerProp extends StatefulProp<TimerProp> {
  TimerProp(this.seconds, this.callback, {this.periodic = false}) {
    restart(seconds, callback, periodic: periodic);
  }
  final double seconds;
  final void Function(Timer) callback;
  final bool periodic;

  // Helper methods
  Timer get timer => _timer;
  void cancel() => _timer?.cancel();
  void restart(double seconds, void Function(Timer) callback, {bool periodic = false}) {
    cancel();
    _timer = periodic ? Timer.periodic(seconds.duration, callback) : Timer(seconds.duration, () => callback(timer));
  }

  //Internal state
  Timer _timer;

  @override
  void dispose() => cancel();
}
```

The primitives class is a really nice look at how we can kill a few birds with one stone here, 
https://github.com/gskinnerTeam/flutter-stateful-props/blob/master/lib/props/primitive_props.dart
* Uses 1 Prop to form the foundation for a bunch of others
* All primitives get `onChange(old,new)` for free, by extending ValueProp<T>
* All primitives get diff-checked `setState` call for free, by extending ValueProp
* We can easily tack on extra behavior, `BoolProp.toggle()`, `IntProp.increment`, `DoubleProp.toInt`, `StringProp.isEmptyOrNull`  as needed
* I'm guessing we can implement Restoration on the base ValueProp, and handle it for all natively supported types in one place (need to learn more here)
* Any other Prop is free to compose or extend these primitives 

When creating your own Props, this is the simple set of methods you can override. **They are all optional, no super() calls needed**. 
```
abstract class StatefulProp<T> {

  @protected
  void init() {}

  @protected
  ChildBuilder getBuilder(ChildBuilder childBuild) => childBuild;

  @protected
  void update(T newProp) {}

  @protected
  void dispose() {}

  @protected
  void restoreState(void Function(RestorableProperty<Object> property, String restorationId) register) {}
}
```

The following set of callbacks/references are available for all Props to use if they need:
```
  BuildContext context;
  void Function(VoidCallback) setState;
  String restoreId;
  //Callbacks to the manager allows composition of other Props from inside `init()`
  T2 addProp<T2>(T2) 
  T2 syncProp<T2>(T2 (c, w){})
```

Working on optimized rebuilds. By simply making the base `ValueProp` a `ChangeNotifier`, we can do something like:
```dart
  void initProps() {
    _counter = addProp(IntProp(autoBuild: false));
    _toggle = addProp(BoolProp(autoBuild: false));
  }
  
return Column(
    children: [
      OutlineButton(onPressed: () => _toggle.toggle(), child: Text("bool.toggle()")),
      OutlineButton(onPressed: () => _counter.increment(), child: Text("int.increment()")),
      // We can nest a build anywhere in the tree, tied to one or more ChangeNotifiers
      NotifiersBuilder(
        [_counter, _toggle],
        // Provide a cached child
        child: RandomColoredBox(child: SizedBox(width: 100, height: 100)),
        builder: (_, cachedChild) {
          String content = "counter: ${_counter.value}, isToggled: ${_toggle.value}";
          return Column(children: [
            RandomColoredBox(child: Text(content)),
            cachedChild,
          ]);},)]));
```
When either of the btns are pressed here, the only thing that rebuilds is the `RandomColoredBox(child: Text(content))` leaf-node.

